data.title: not my first choice
data.text: The menu was filled with food names I did not recognize and did not appeal to me or my friend. The prices were much higher than I had expected. My friend ended up eating a hamburger!

data.title: Really?
data.text: Had the Calabash Shrimp. Fried shrimp made from boiled shrimp? REALLY? I usually really like THC, but these shrimp were salty, tough and forgettable. Seapak frozen shrimp would have been better...

data.title: Have some $$$$$
data.text: Definitely NOT for the average east Tennessean.  If you want to impress someone, yes by all means go.  But you certainly better have the $ ready to shell out!  Food was good, but this establishment is for the socially elite.

data.title: Yummy
data.text: Tupelo is great for some southern comfort food with a unique twist. Great breakfast items served all day along with sandwiches and dinner entrees. Each meal comes with biscuits and homemade jam. So good!

data.title: Creative Southern cuisine in a beautifully restored train station
data.text:
Tupelo Honey is the Johnson City branch of the famous Asheville, NC new Southern restaurant.  The food is excellent, much of which is sourced from local farms, and creative takes on Southern classics. For example the nachos are made with pimento cheese, Hickory Nut Gap Farm chorizo sausage, and black eyed peas.  The burger is large and perfectly cooked, from a local pasture raised beef supplier. Breakfast is served all day with creative offerings such as sweet potato pancakes, pecans, bacon, and their dreamy fried chicken.  Pretty much everything is outstanding.  The service is friendly and informal, perfect for the setting.  Prices are consistent with the quality. Also, TH is housed in a really lovely restoration of an old train station.  Large, airy room that invites good conversation over a relaxed dinner.

Tip:  TH has a large outdoor patio that is terrific in good weather and even has an outdoor fireplaces surrounded with easy chairs for a drink in cooler weather.

data.title: Guess I Need to Try Dinner
data.text: Went here for lunch with friends. Lovely place with nice outdoor seating.  Service was good.   I found the lunch menu to a have very limited selection.  I opted for the burger and potatoes.  The burger was a good size and came with all the trimmings; however, I would classify it mediocre at best.  Not a lot of taste.  The potatoes were very greasy.  I definitely would not recommend them.  Had heard good things about this place so may try it again sometime for dinner.  Overall, I was a bit disappointed.

data.title: Always good food
data.text: Our visit to Tupelo Honey yesterday was excellent. We started with the fried green tomatoes and wings appetizers, both were very good. The Cobb salad was very good as well. Our server, Turner never let our beverages go empty and was on the spot with everything we needed.

data.title: Always good for biscuits & blueberry preserves
data.text: I'm a little picky about tomato soup in general, but it's consistently hearty, tasty, and filling at Tupelo Honey--their soup and salad combo is very good and reasonably priced for a filling lunch. Their standard starter--biscuits hot from the oven, whole blueberry preserves, and honey--is irresistible. With beautiful weather, we dined outdoors on the loading dock for the old train station, a bit noisy with traffic, but our server was attentive and pleasant. Be prepared to shoo away the bees...they love to dive in for the honey. :) If you're allergic to stings, you'd better sit inside just to be on the safe side, although the bees were much more interested in the honey than us.

data.title: Nice change
data.text: I hadn't been to Tupelo Honey for a while. When it opened it seemed impossible to park and then the wait was terrible. This issue seems to have settled out. I took a group of six for a business dinner, The menu offered something for everyone and yet each item is uniquely "Tupelo Honey". The appetizers we original and tasted great. I found more seafood than I remembered, which was good for my desire for lower calories.  Overall we had great service and a very good meal.

data.title: Sunday Brunch
data.text: Drove over to Johnson City after church for brunch. They took fried okra off menu which was one of my favorites. The fries were greasy as if warmed over. Not one of my favorite visits to a Tupelo Honey restaurant. Been to both Asheville locations and Virginia Beach before this one.

data.title: Can't wait to go back!
data.text:
First of all I love it when old buildings are repurposed and brought back to life. The service was great, we were seated quickly and brought our drinks so we could try and decide what to eat...so many yummy things. I opted for the ribs with crispy brussel sprouts, and I didn't even think I liked them, they were delicious and the ribs as well.
The atmosphere was warm and inviting, we had a great time.

data.title: Honey Tupelo
data.text: My husband and I tried Honey Tupelo for the first time a few weeks back. My husband said the burger he got was probably the best he had ever had. I got a chicken sandwich which was equally good. The biscuits served before our entrée came along with the homemade jam was out of this world. My daughter and son-in-law is celebrating their 6th anniversary. We treated them to Honey Tupelo and they loved it. We will be visiting again.

data.title: Love this place
data.text: I stopped in for dinner. I had the salmon with brussel sprouts and Mac and cheese. All were delicious. Service at the bar was exceptional. Beer selection is nice. Great location downtown.

data.title: This restaurant is a lot of fun!
data.text:
The atmosphere/ambiance is unique! Have I mentioned I have visited several times and everything I have ordered was delicious!!!
Go you won't be disappointed!!

data.title: Not overly impressed
data.text: The venue is very interesting being in an old train station. After that though it's really nothing to write home about. The food is average and overpriced. It's a very cramped venue and after a couple of visits I've honestly written this one off.

data.title: Classy dining in downtown Johnson City
data.text:
After the fifth visit, Tupelo Honey Cafe has been excellent. Although it may be time to add a little change to their menu, still excellent food, service and atmosphere.

The staff is always friendly and professional, and they know how to present a great meal. If you are looking for a local Restuarant with a little southern twist, give Tupelo Honey a try, you will not be disappointed!

data.title: Love Tupelo So Much Ate Here Twice
data.text: I discovered Tupelo Honey Cafe while in Jonesborough for the International Story Tellers weekend. I loved it so much that I ate here twice--my first night and last night in Tennessee. I love, love, love their food. The biscuits and blueberry jam are out of this world and the Brussels sprouts are awesome. I had the rosemary, lime, and gin martini on both visits and it was fabulous. On my last visit I had the pork ribs with the jalapeno corn coleslaw. The ribs were spicy and tender. The outside seating is really nice and a great get away. Services was also very attentive and all staff helped each other to provide top-notch service.

data.title: Good service
data.text: Took someone there today for lunch.  She was not from our area. Staff did great job with service refilling drinks and food was really good.  Perfect afternoon for sitting out side.

data.title: A favorite when visiting area
data.text: Discovered this place after someone recommended the Asheville location. Couldn't get there but when we got to Johnson City discovered this one. My wife loves the shrimp and grits and they did not disappoint . Nice menu, friendly servers and good outside seating area.

data.title: Great Building...Terrific Food
data.text: The first thing you notice about this restaurant is the great building that houses it.  The architecturally nice railroad station has been beautifully restored to it's original charm as part of the restoration of many of the historic buildings in Johnson City.  The second thing you notice is the unusual selection of items on the menu.  It is a nice selection of their take on southern dishes and I believe they have done a great job.  My favorite was the okra.  Very crunchy with a unique blend of spices and perfectly salted.  Yum.  The chicken BLT was juicy and again with a unique blend of spices that made the taste delightful and unlike what you typically experience at other restaurants.  Served up with great southern style biscuits and of course Tupelo Honey.  Definitely a great place to eat in Johnson City.  Enjoy the building and savor the delicious food.  Thank you Tessa for being a wonderful and attentive waitress.
